19, 1961 in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]]) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive back]] in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Washington Redskins]] and the [[Detroit Lions]].  He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Hawaii]].\n\nIn 1999, Cherry was convicted of first degree murder in the death of his wife.  He was initially sentenced to [[life imprisonment]],<ref>[http://starbulletin.com/1999/08/25/sports/story1.html ''Raphel Cherry convicted of murdering wife'']</ref> but upon appeal of his conviction, his sentenced was reduced to 30 years. Cherry's estimated release date is January 9, 2020.<ref>[http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?court=ar&vol=supreme/2002a/20020214/cr01-858&invol=2 ''Raphel CHERRY v. STATE of Arkansas'']</ref>\n\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Raphel Cherry\n| image_name     = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      =\n| image_caption  = \n| nationality    =\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1961|12|19}}\n| birth_place = Little Rock, Arkansas\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause          = \n| alias          = \n| motive         = \n| charge         = \n| conviction     = Murder - First Degree (Arkansas)\n| conviction_penalty        = Life imprisonment, reduced to 360 months imprisonment upon appeal\n| conviction_status         = Incarcerated at the [[Cummins Unit]] near [[Pine Bluff, Arkansas|Pine Bluff]], [[Arkansas]]\n| occupation     = \n| spouse         = Jerri Cherry (Deceased)\n| parents        = \n| children       = 1 daughter\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hawaii Rainbow Warriors quarterback navbox}}\n{{Redskins1985DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cherry, Raphel}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Little Rock, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:American football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football players]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Arkansas]]\n[[Category:American murderers]]\n{{defensiveback-1960s-stub}}\n{{crime-stub}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Castlelore", "label": "safe", "comment": "release date from prison from January 9, 2020 to January 9, 2029", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raphel_Cherry"}
{"title_page": "Vis (island)", "text_new": "{{about|the island of Vis|the town on the island of the same name|Vis (town)}}\n{{Inadequate lead|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Vis\n| image_name       = Vis Bisevo satelite.gif\n| image_caption    = Satellite image of Vis and [[Bi\u0161evo]]\n| image_size       = 250px\n| map_image        = Croatia - Vis.PNG\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_link =\n| nickname         =\n| location         = [[Adriatic Sea]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|43|02|N|16|09|E|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      =\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_km2         = 89.72\n| highest_mount    = [[Mount Hum|Hum]]\n| elevation_m      = 587\n| country          = Croatia\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Counties of Croatia|County]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Split-Dalmatia County|Split-Dalmatia]]\n| country_largest_city              = [[Vis (town)|Vis]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = 1,920\n| country_leader_title              =\n| country_leader_name               =\n| population       = 3,617\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| density_km2      = \n| ethnic_groups    =\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n\n'''Vis''' ({{IPA-sh|\u028b\u00ee\u02d0s|pron}}; {{Lang-grc|\u1f3c\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1}}; [[Latin]]: ''Issa'', {{lang-it|Lissa}}) is a small [[Croatia]]n island in the [[Adriatic Sea]]. The farthest inhabited island off the Croatian mainland, Vis had a population of 3,617 in 2011. Vis has an area of {{convert|90.26|km2|2|abbr=off}}. Its highest point is [[Mount Hum|Hum]], which is {{convert|587|m|0|abbr=off}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. The island's two largest settlements are the [[Vis (town)|town of Vis]] on the island's eastern side (the settlement for which the island was originally named) and [[Komi\u017ea]] on its western coast.\n\nOnce known for its thriving fishing industry in the late 19th and early 20th century, the main present-day industries on the island are agriculture and tourism. Vis town and Komi\u017ea are also seats of separate administrative municipalities which cover the entire island and nearby islets, which are both part of [[Split-Dalmatia County]].\n\nIn 2017 the movie ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]'' was filmed on location on Vis.<ref name=\"TCN\">{{cite news|last1=Demark|first1=Nikolina|title=Will the Filming of 'Mamma Mia' Affect the Island of Vis?|url=http://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21239-will-the-filming-of-mamma-mia-affect-the-island-of-vis|accessdate=16 August 2017|work=Total Croatia News|date=15 August 2017}}</ref> In 2019 GEOPARK Vis archipelago became a member of [[UNESCO Global Geoparks]].<ref>https://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/35391-global-geopark-network</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:BAF Vis Reviw.jpg|thumb|left|[[Balkan Air Force]] aircraft at Vis Air Base during review by [[Josip Broz Tito]]]]\n[[File:Vojni potkop Parja Vis 01.JPG|thumbnail|right|Entrance to the patrol boat pen on Vis, [[Croatia]].]]\nVis was inhabited by the time of the [[Neolithic]] period. In the 4th century BC, the Greek tyrant of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Dionysius the Elder]], founded the colony ''Issa'' on the island.<ref>''An Inventory of Archaic and Classical Poleis'': An Investigation Conducted by The Copenhagen Polis Centre for the Danish National Research Foundation by Mogens Herman Hansen, 2005, Index</ref><ref>''The Princeton Encyclopedia of Classical Sites'' (eds. Richard Stillwell, William L. MacDonald, Marian Holland McAllister), ISSA (Vis) Croatia. A town on an island of the same name in the central Adriatic. It was settled by [[Illyrians]], who were under the domination of Liburni from the 8th to the 6th centuries B.C. At the beginning of the 4th century B.C. it was colonized by Syracusan Greeks as part of a plan of Dionysios the Elder to control the Adriatic. During the 3rd century Issa founded the emporia [[Tragurion]] (Tra\u00f9, now Trogir) and Epetion (Stobre\u010d) on the Illynan mainland. Its predominance in the region lasted until the first [[First Illyrian War|Illyro-Roman war]] 229-219 B.C. when it became a pawn in the battles of greater powers. In the civil war it sided with [[Pompey]] and consequently lost its privileges and autonomy in 47 B.C. when it was reduced to the rank of an oppidum civium Romanorum and was dependent on the newly founded colony at [[Salona]]. As a polis Issa minted its own money, and these coins of many types had wide circulation. The town, situated on a slope on the W side of a large bay, was defended by strong [[Hellenistic]] walls, still visible in an irregular quadrangle (265 x 360 m) that enclosed an area of 9.8 ha. The street grid and foundations of houses have been found. The necropolis has yielded many pieces of pottery, including some from S Italy. The wall of the cavea of the theater, built in the Roman period, is incorporated into the present Franciscan Monastery. It could seat about 3000 persons. Inscriptions, statues, coins, and pottery are preserved in the archaeological museums at Split and Zagreb.</ref> Later, it became an independent [[polis]], and even minted its own money and founded its own colonies, the most notable of which was [[Asp\u00e1lathos]] (the modern-day city of [[Split, Croatia|Split]]). \n\nIn the 1st century BC, the island was held by the [[Liburnians]].<ref>Wilkes, J. J. ''The Illyrians'', 1992, {{ISBN|0-631-19807-5}}, p. 183, \"... We may begin with the Venetic peoples, Veneti, Carni, Histri and Liburni, whose language set them apart from the rest of the Illyrians. ...\"</ref> Its importance in the region ended with the first Illyro-Roman war (29\u2013219 BC). Having sided with Pompeus during the period of civil struggles in Rome, became an \"oppidum civium Romanorum\" in 47 BC.\n\nUntil 1797, the island was under the rule of the [[Republic of Venice]]. During this time large settlements developed along the coastline (Comisa (now Komi\u017ea) and Lissa (now Vis)). Administratively, the island of Lissa was for centuries bound to the island of Lesina, now named [[Hvar]]. The Venetian influence is still recognizable in architecture found on the island, and some vocabulary of the Croatian dialect spoken locally is [[Venetian language|Venetian]] in origin.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nAfter the short-lived Napoleonic [[Kingdom of Italy (Napoleonic)|Kingdom of Italy]], with Italian as the official language, the island was ruled by the [[Austrian Empire]] from 1814. It maintained its Italian name of Lissa. After the end of [[World War I]], it was under Italian rule again in the period from 1918 to 1921, according to the provisions of the [[Treaty of London (1915)|1915 Treaty of London]], before it was ceded to [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] as part of the [[Treaty of Rapallo (1920)|1920 Treaty of Rapallo]].\n\nThe sea to the north of the island was the location of two battles:\n*on 13 March 1811, a small [[Royal Navy]] squadron under the command of Captain [[William Hoste]], defeated a larger French squadron in the [[Battle of Lissa (1811)]]\n*on 20 July 1866, the smaller Austrian fleet, under [[Wilhelm von Tegetthoff|Admiral Tegetthoff]], attacked the [[Regia Marina|Italian fleet]], under [[Carlo Pellion di Persano|Admiral Persano]], defeating the larger Italian force and sinking the {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re d'Italia||2|up=y}} in the [[Battle of Lissa (1866)]].\n\n===Second World War===\nVis was at one point the site of the general headquarters of Marshal [[Josip Broz Tito]], the leader of the Yugoslav [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisan]] resistance movement. It was occupied by Italy between 1941 and 1943, then was liberated by the Partisans and held by a British flotilla in 1943\u201344. At the end of World War II the island returned to Yugoslavia. During the war the island was mined. Allied fighter planes were based at a small airfield that was also used for emergency landings of Allied bombers, including an American [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|B-24]] flown by [[George McGovern]]. [[No. 6 Squadron RAF]] extensively used the airfield as a forward operating base, flying [[Hawker Hurricane]] Mk IV fighter aircraft, from May 1944 to February 1945.<ref>Jefford, C.G. ''RAF Squadrons, a Comprehensive Record of the Movement and Equipment of all RAF Squadrons and their Antecedents since 1912''. Shrewsbury: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-141-2}}.</ref><ref>The \"Tin-opener\". No 6 Squadron (RAF ) Association Newsletter. July 2014.</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, a crate of the [[Armed Services Editions]] of paperback books was dropped by parachute along with other supplies on to Vis Island off the coast of Yugoslavia. The books were then read aloud to the partisans by English speaking soldiers who translated the books as they read them.<ref>Council on Books in Wartime, and Robert O. Ballou. A History of the Council on Books in Wartime, 1942\u20131946. 1946. p. 81.</ref>\n\nEarly in July 1944, the novelist [[Evelyn Waugh]] flew with [[Randolph Churchill]] from [[Bari, Italy]], to Vis as part of the British military mission to Yugoslavia.<ref name=Churchill251>Churchill 1997, p. 251</ref> There they met Marshal Tito.<ref name=Churchill251/> Waugh and Churchill returned to Bari before flying back to Yugoslavia to begin their mission, but their aeroplane crash-landed, both men were injured, and their mission was delayed for a month.<ref>Lovell 2012, p471-6</ref><ref>Soames 2003, p389-90</ref><ref>Churchill 1997, p. 252, 256</ref>\n\nDuring WWII the island was also home to 1435 Squadron of the RAF flying Mark IX Spitfires in ground support of allied troops fighting in Italy.\n\nAfter the war, the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] used the island as one of its main [[Yugoslav Navy|naval]] [[naval base|bases]] until abandoning the base in 1989.<ref name=SFRYSubase>{{cite web|title=Take a Look Inside These Abandoned Submarines & Bases|url=http://www.historyinorbit.com/take-a-look-inside-these-abandoned-submarines-and-bases/34/?src=taboola&v=p|work=History in Orbit website|author=Ryan|pages=34\u20137|date=15 March 2015|access-date=6 July 2018}}</ref> After Croatia became independent in 1991, [[Croatian Navy|its navy]] did not reclaim most of the facilities, and the many abandoned buildings are being used for civilian purposes and tourism, including tunnels, bunkers and a secret [[submarine]] base.<ref name=SFRYSubase/> In 2008, 34 mines left over from World War II were cleared from the island.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Komiza, Island of Vis, Croatia.JPG|thumb|right|[[Komi\u017ea]]]]\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Historical population<br/> of Vis island\n|shading = off\n|source = Naselja i stanovni\u0161tvo Republike Hrvatske 1857\u20132001, DZS, Zagreb, 2005\n|1857 |6304\n|1869 |6485\n|1880 |7871\n|1890 |8647\n|1900 |9914\n|1910 |10107\n|1921 |9788\n|1931 |8756\n|1948 |7485\n|1953 |7890\n|1961 |7004\n|1971 |5049\n|1981 |4134\n|1991 |4361\n|2001 |3637\n|2011 |3460\n}}\n\nThe island's main industries are agriculture (mainly [[viticulture]]), fishing, fish refining and tourism.<ref name=\"peljar\">{{in lang|hr}} [http://peljar.cvs.hr/show_place_info.php?id=483 First Croatian online peljar]</ref>\n\nAround 20% of the island's [[arable land]] is covered with [[vineyard]]s. Autochthonous vine species cultivated on the island are [[Plavac Mali]], Kurtelo\u0161ka, and Vugava (the indigenous grape of what is now known as [[viognier]]).<ref name=\"tz-vis_economy\">[http://www.tz-vis.hr/eng/economy.htm Economy of Vis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607172543/http://www.tz-vis.hr/eng/economy.htm |date=7 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe sea around Vis is rich with fish, especially blue fish ([[sardine]], [[mackerel]] and [[anchovy]]).  Komi\u017ea fishermen of the 16th century developed their own type of fishing boat, the [[falku\u0161a]], which was used until the second half of the 20th century because of its excellent features.<ref name=\"tz-vis_economy\"/>\n\n== Access ==\nVis is accessed only by ferry boat. [[Jadrolinija]] services the island using mainly the [[Roll-on/roll-off|car ferry]] ''[[Petar Hektorovi\u0107 (ferry)|Petar Hektorovi\u0107]]''. There is also high speed passenger catamaran service provided by Jadrolinija.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[List of ancient cities in Illyria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Jefford, C.G. ''RAF Squadrons, a Comprehensive Record of the Movement and Equipment of all RAF Squadrons and their Antecedents since 1912''. Shrewsbury: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-141-2}}.\n* The \"Tin-opener\". No 6 Squadron (RAF ) Association Newsletter. July 2014.\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book | last=Churchill| first=Winston| title=His Father's Son: The Life of Randolph Churchill| publisher=Orion| location=London| year=1997| isbn=978-1-85799-969-3}}\n*{{cite book | last=Lovell| first= Mary S.| title=The Churchills: A Family at the Heart of History \u2013 from the Duke of Marlborough to Winston Churchill| publisher= Abacus| date=5 April 2012| isbn=978-0-349-11978-6 }}\n*{{cite book | last=Soames| first=Mary| title=Clementine Churchill| publisher=Doubleday| location=London| year=2003| isbn=978-0-385-60741-4}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Vis}}\n{{commons category|Island of Vis}}\n* [http://www.tz-komiza.hr/ Komiza - Island Vis Tourist Association]\n* [http://croatia.hr/en-GB/Destinations/Island/Vis?ZHNcNTY1LHBcNw%3d%3d Vis - Croatian National Tourist Board]\n* [http://www.tz-vis.hr/ Vis Tourist Association]\n\n{{Islands of Croatia}}\n{{Inhabited Islands of Croatia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vis (Island)}}\n[[Category:Islands of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Adriatic Sea]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Split-Dalmatia County]]\n[[Category:Vis (island)| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the island of Vis|the town on the island of the same name|Vis (town)}}\n{{Inadequate lead|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Vis\n| image_name       = Vis Bisevo satelite.gif\n| image_caption    = Satellite image of Vis and [[Bi\u0161evo]]\n| image_size       = 250px\n| map_image        = Croatia - Vis.PNG\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_link =\n| nickname         =\n| location         = [[Adriatic Sea]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|43|02|N|16|09|E|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      =\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_km2         = 89.72\n| highest_mount    = [[Mount Hum|Hum]]\n| elevation_m      = 587\n| country          = Croatia\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Counties of Croatia|County]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Split-Dalmatia County|Split-Dalmatia]]\n| country_largest_city              = [[Vis (town)|Vis]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = 1,920\n| country_leader_title              =\n| country_leader_name               =\n| population       = 3,617\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| density_km2      = \n| ethnic_groups    =\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n\n'''Vis''' ({{IPA-sh|\u028b\u00ee\u02d0s|pron}}; {{Lang-grc|\u1f3c\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1}}; [[Latin]]: ''Issa'', {{lang-it|Lissa}}) is a small [[Croatia]]n island in the [[Adriatic Sea]]. The farthest inhabited island off the Croatian mainland, Vis had a population of 3,617 in 2011. Vis has an area of {{convert|90.26|km2|2|abbr=off}}. Its highest point is [[Mount Hum|Hum]], which is {{convert|587|m|0|abbr=off}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. The island's two largest settlements are the [[Vis (town)|town of Vis]] on the island's eastern side (the settlement for which the island was originally named) and [[Komi\u017ea]] on its western coast.\n\nOnce known for its thriving fishing industry in the late 19th and early 20th century, the main present-day industries on the island are agriculture and tourism. Vis town and Komi\u017ea are also seats of separate administrative municipalities which cover the entire island and nearby islets, which are both part of [[Split-Dalmatia County]].\n\nIn 2017 the movie ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]'' was filmed on location on Vis.<ref name=\"TCN\">{{cite news|last1=Demark|first1=Nikolina|title=Will the Filming of 'Mamma Mia' Affect the Island of Vis?|url=http://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21239-will-the-filming-of-mamma-mia-affect-the-island-of-vis|accessdate=16 August 2017|work=Total Croatia News|date=15 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 GEOPARK Vis archipelago became a member of UNESCO Global Geoparks.<ref>https://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/35391-global-geopark-network</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:BAF Vis Reviw.jpg|thumb|left|[[Balkan Air Force]] aircraft at Vis Air Base during review by [[Josip Broz Tito]]]]\n[[File:Vojni potkop Parja Vis 01.JPG|thumbnail|right|Entrance to the patrol boat pen on Vis, [[Croatia]].]]\nVis was inhabited by the time of the [[Neolithic]] period. In the 4th century BC, the Greek tyrant of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Dionysius the Elder]], founded the colony ''Issa'' on the island.<ref>''An Inventory of Archaic and Classical Poleis'': An Investigation Conducted by The Copenhagen Polis Centre for the Danish National Research Foundation by Mogens Herman Hansen, 2005, Index</ref><ref>''The Princeton Encyclopedia of Classical Sites'' (eds. Richard Stillwell, William L. MacDonald, Marian Holland McAllister), ISSA (Vis) Croatia. A town on an island of the same name in the central Adriatic. It was settled by [[Illyrians]], who were under the domination of Liburni from the 8th to the 6th centuries B.C. At the beginning of the 4th century B.C. it was colonized by Syracusan Greeks as part of a plan of Dionysios the Elder to control the Adriatic. During the 3rd century Issa founded the emporia [[Tragurion]] (Tra\u00f9, now Trogir) and Epetion (Stobre\u010d) on the Illynan mainland. Its predominance in the region lasted until the first [[First Illyrian War|Illyro-Roman war]] 229-219 B.C. when it became a pawn in the battles of greater powers. In the civil war it sided with [[Pompey]] and consequently lost its privileges and autonomy in 47 B.C. when it was reduced to the rank of an oppidum civium Romanorum and was dependent on the newly founded colony at [[Salona]]. As a polis Issa minted its own money, and these coins of many types had wide circulation. The town, situated on a slope on the W side of a large bay, was defended by strong [[Hellenistic]] walls, still visible in an irregular quadrangle (265 x 360 m) that enclosed an area of 9.8 ha. The street grid and foundations of houses have been found. The necropolis has yielded many pieces of pottery, including some from S Italy. The wall of the cavea of the theater, built in the Roman period, is incorporated into the present Franciscan Monastery. It could seat about 3000 persons. Inscriptions, statues, coins, and pottery are preserved in the archaeological museums at Split and Zagreb.</ref> Later, it became an independent [[polis]], and even minted its own money and founded its own colonies, the most notable of which was [[Asp\u00e1lathos]] (the modern-day city of [[Split, Croatia|Split]]). \n\nIn the 1st century BC, the island was held by the [[Liburnians]].<ref>Wilkes, J. J. ''The Illyrians'', 1992, {{ISBN|0-631-19807-5}}, p. 183, \"... We may begin with the Venetic peoples, Veneti, Carni, Histri and Liburni, whose language set them apart from the rest of the Illyrians. ...\"</ref> Its importance in the region ended with the first Illyro-Roman war (29\u2013219 BC). Having sided with Pompeus during the period of civil struggles in Rome, became an \"oppidum civium Romanorum\" in 47 BC.\n\nUntil 1797, the island was under the rule of the [[Republic of Venice]]. During this time large settlements developed along the coastline (Comisa (now Komi\u017ea) and Lissa (now Vis)). Administratively, the island of Lissa was for centuries bound to the island of Lesina, now named [[Hvar]]. The Venetian influence is still recognizable in architecture found on the island, and some vocabulary of the Croatian dialect spoken locally is [[Venetian language|Venetian]] in origin.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nAfter the short-lived Napoleonic [[Kingdom of Italy (Napoleonic)|Kingdom of Italy]], with Italian as the official language, the island was ruled by the [[Austrian Empire]] from 1814. It maintained its Italian name of Lissa. After the end of [[World War I]], it was under Italian rule again in the period from 1918 to 1921, according to the provisions of the [[Treaty of London (1915)|1915 Treaty of London]], before it was ceded to [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] as part of the [[Treaty of Rapallo (1920)|1920 Treaty of Rapallo]].\n\nThe sea to the north of the island was the location of two battles:\n*on 13 March 1811, a small [[Royal Navy]] squadron under the command of Captain [[William Hoste]], defeated a larger French squadron in the [[Battle of Lissa (1811)]]\n*on 20 July 1866, the smaller Austrian fleet, under [[Wilhelm von Tegetthoff|Admiral Tegetthoff]], attacked the [[Regia Marina|Italian fleet]], under [[Carlo Pellion di Persano|Admiral Persano]], defeating the larger Italian force and sinking the {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re d'Italia||2|up=y}} in the [[Battle of Lissa (1866)]].\n\n===Second World War===\nVis was at one point the site of the general headquarters of Marshal [[Josip Broz Tito]], the leader of the Yugoslav [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisan]] resistance movement. It was occupied by Italy between 1941 and 1943, then was liberated by the Partisans and held by a British flotilla in 1943\u201344. At the end of World War II the island returned to Yugoslavia. During the war the island was mined. Allied fighter planes were based at a small airfield that was also used for emergency landings of Allied bombers, including an American [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|B-24]] flown by [[George McGovern]]. [[No. 6 Squadron RAF]] extensively used the airfield as a forward operating base, flying [[Hawker Hurricane]] Mk IV fighter aircraft, from May 1944 to February 1945.<ref>Jefford, C.G. ''RAF Squadrons, a Comprehensive Record of the Movement and Equipment of all RAF Squadrons and their Antecedents since 1912''. Shrewsbury: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-141-2}}.</ref><ref>The \"Tin-opener\". No 6 Squadron (RAF ) Association Newsletter. July 2014.</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, a crate of the [[Armed Services Editions]] of paperback books was dropped by parachute along with other supplies on to Vis Island off the coast of Yugoslavia. The books were then read aloud to the partisans by English speaking soldiers who translated the books as they read them.<ref>Council on Books in Wartime, and Robert O. Ballou. A History of the Council on Books in Wartime, 1942\u20131946. 1946. p. 81.</ref>\n\nEarly in July 1944, the novelist [[Evelyn Waugh]] flew with [[Randolph Churchill]] from [[Bari, Italy]], to Vis as part of the British military mission to Yugoslavia.<ref name=Churchill251>Churchill 1997, p. 251</ref> There they met Marshal Tito.<ref name=Churchill251/> Waugh and Churchill returned to Bari before flying back to Yugoslavia to begin their mission, but their aeroplane crash-landed, both men were injured, and their mission was delayed for a month.<ref>Lovell 2012, p471-6</ref><ref>Soames 2003, p389-90</ref><ref>Churchill 1997, p. 252, 256</ref>\n\nDuring WWII the island was also home to 1435 Squadron of the RAF flying Mark IX Spitfires in ground support of allied troops fighting in Italy.\n\nAfter the war, the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] used the island as one of its main [[Yugoslav Navy|naval]] [[naval base|bases]] until abandoning the base in 1989.<ref name=SFRYSubase>{{cite web|title=Take a Look Inside These Abandoned Submarines & Bases|url=http://www.historyinorbit.com/take-a-look-inside-these-abandoned-submarines-and-bases/34/?src=taboola&v=p|work=History in Orbit website|author=Ryan|pages=34\u20137|date=15 March 2015|access-date=6 July 2018}}</ref> After Croatia became independent in 1991, [[Croatian Navy|its navy]] did not reclaim most of the facilities, and the many abandoned buildings are being used for civilian purposes and tourism, including tunnels, bunkers and a secret [[submarine]] base.<ref name=SFRYSubase/> In 2008, 34 mines left over from World War II were cleared from the island.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Komiza, Island of Vis, Croatia.JPG|thumb|right|[[Komi\u017ea]]]]\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Historical population<br/> of Vis island\n|shading = off\n|source = Naselja i stanovni\u0161tvo Republike Hrvatske 1857\u20132001, DZS, Zagreb, 2005\n|1857 |6304\n|1869 |6485\n|1880 |7871\n|1890 |8647\n|1900 |9914\n|1910 |10107\n|1921 |9788\n|1931 |8756\n|1948 |7485\n|1953 |7890\n|1961 |7004\n|1971 |5049\n|1981 |4134\n|1991 |4361\n|2001 |3637\n|2011 |3460\n}}\n\nThe island's main industries are agriculture (mainly [[viticulture]]), fishing, fish refining and tourism.<ref name=\"peljar\">{{in lang|hr}} [http://peljar.cvs.hr/show_place_info.php?id=483 First Croatian online peljar]</ref>\n\nAround 20% of the island's [[arable land]] is covered with [[vineyard]]s. Autochthonous vine species cultivated on the island are [[Plavac Mali]], Kurtelo\u0161ka, and Vugava (the indigenous grape of what is now known as [[viognier]]).<ref name=\"tz-vis_economy\">[http://www.tz-vis.hr/eng/economy.htm Economy of Vis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607172543/http://www.tz-vis.hr/eng/economy.htm |date=7 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe sea around Vis is rich with fish, especially blue fish ([[sardine]], [[mackerel]] and [[anchovy]]).  Komi\u017ea fishermen of the 16th century developed their own type of fishing boat, the [[falku\u0161a]], which was used until the second half of the 20th century because of its excellent features.<ref name=\"tz-vis_economy\"/>\n\n== Access ==\nVis is accessed only by ferry boat. [[Jadrolinija]] services the island using mainly the [[Roll-on/roll-off|car ferry]] ''[[Petar Hektorovi\u0107 (ferry)|Petar Hektorovi\u0107]]''. There is also high speed passenger catamaran service provided by Jadrolinija.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[List of ancient cities in Illyria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Jefford, C.G. ''RAF Squadrons, a Comprehensive Record of the Movement and Equipment of all RAF Squadrons and their Antecedents since 1912''. Shrewsbury: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-141-2}}.\n* The \"Tin-opener\". No 6 Squadron (RAF ) Association Newsletter. July 2014.\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book | last=Churchill| first=Winston| title=His Father's Son: The Life of Randolph Churchill| publisher=Orion| location=London| year=1997| isbn=978-1-85799-969-3}}\n*{{cite book | last=Lovell| first= Mary S.| title=The Churchills: A Family at the Heart of History \u2013 from the Duke of Marlborough to Winston Churchill| publisher= Abacus| date=5 April 2012| isbn=978-0-349-11978-6 }}\n*{{cite book | last=Soames| first=Mary| title=Clementine Churchill| publisher=Doubleday| location=London| year=2003| isbn=978-0-385-60741-4}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Vis}}\n{{commons category|Island of Vis}}\n* [http://www.tz-komiza.hr/ Komiza - Island Vis Tourist Association]\n* [http://croatia.hr/en-GB/Destinations/Island/Vis?ZHNcNTY1LHBcNw%3d%3d Vis - Croatian National Tourist Board]\n* [http://www.tz-vis.hr/ Vis Tourist Association]\n\n{{Islands of Croatia}}\n{{Inhabited Islands of Croatia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vis (Island)}}\n[[Category:Islands of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Adriatic Sea]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Split-Dalmatia County]]\n[[Category:Vis (island)| ]]\n", "name_user": "Vanjagenije", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vis_(island)"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Curcio", "text_new": "{{POV|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Anthony Curcio\n|image=Anthony Curcio speaking to college football players.png\n|caption=Curcio speaking to college football players in August 2014\n|birth_place=[[Monroe, Washington]], U.S.\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1980|9|1}}\n|occupation= Speaker, author\n|spouse=\n|children=2\n|residence=\n}}\n'''Anthony J. Curcio''' (born September 1, 1980) is an American author, public speaker, and convicted robber.<ref name=CC>{{cite news|last1=Clarridge |first1=Christine |title=Inner-tube robber now free, warning about life of drugs, crime |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2024575267_dbtubertalksxml.html |agency=The Seattle Times |date=September 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219051132/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2024575267_dbtubertalksxml.html |archivedate=December 19, 2014 }}</ref>  In 2008, Curcio was responsible for one of the most elaborately planned armored car heists in U.S. history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doughery|first1=Phil|title=D.B. Tuber|url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=8829|website=HistoryLink.org|publisher=History Link}}</ref> He was eventually arrested and sentenced to six years in federal prison. Upon his release from prison he has devoted his life to working with youth in the field of drug abuse and crime prevention, speaking to students and athletes across the U.S.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esteban|first1=Michelle|title=D.B. Tuber dedicates life to warn others of dangers of drugs|url=http://www.komonews.com/news/local/DB-Tuber-out-of-prison-Warns-students-278808571.html|agency=KOMO 4 News|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> He has been featured in ''[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'',  ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV program)|20/20]]'', [[Fox News]], [[NPR]] and [[NBC]] among others.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nCurcio was born and raised in [[Monroe, Washington]]. As a teenager, he was popular and talented and voted captain of both football and basketball teams at [[Monroe High School (Washington)|Monroe High School]]<nowiki/>. Curcio broke many records in football and received several honors and awards for his play in both sports.<ref name=DOJ>{{cite web|title=Former High School Star Athlete Sentenced to Prison for Armored Car Robbery|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/waw/press/2009/jul/curcio.html|website=justice.gov|date=July 2009|publisher=The United States Attorney's Office|accessdate=<!--July 2009-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stangeland|first1=Brooke|title=Out of Prison, Real-Life Thomas Crown Looks Back on Almost-Perfect Heist|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/prison-real-life-thomas-crown-back-perfect-heist/story?id=19450132|agency=ABC news|date=June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCurcio would later go on to play football at his father's alma mater, the [[University of Idaho]], which had been his childhood dream.<ref>{{cite web|title=1999 Idaho Vandals - Sports Illustrated|url=http://157.166.253.202/football/college/rosters/1999/iia/|publisher=CNN/Sports Illustrated|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141130084954/http://157.166.253.202/football/college/rosters/1999/iia/|archive-date=2014-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> While returning a punt in practice, Curcio tore his [[anterior cruciate ligament]], ending his promising college football career and introducing him to the powerful pain killer [[Vicodin]]. Curcio quickly became addicted to the prescription pills.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stangeland|first1=Brooke|title=Reporter's Notebook: On the Trail of a Bank Robber|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/06/reporters-notebook-on-the-trail-of-a-bank-robber/|agency=ABC News|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref>\nSoon after, he began experiencing [[Drug withdrawal|withdrawals]] and even injured himself intentionally by kicking an oak coffee table repeatedly in order to obtain more pills. With family pressure, Curcio agreed to enter a drug/alcohol treatment facility.<ref name=HeistandHigh>{{cite book|last1=Batty|first1=Dane|last2=Curcio|first2=Anthony|title=Heist and High|url=http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|date=June 21, 2013|publisher=Nish Publishing Company|location=Portland, Oregon|isbn=098579450X|access-date=November 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205051436/http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing a 21-day in-patient program, Curcio, now sober, started his first business, called \"Tony\u2019s Gaming\", which bought and sold casino tables and other gaming merchandise. Curcio expanded his business by leasing a commercial space and adjacent storage. Within a few months of being open to the public, Tony's Gaming was unexpectedly shut down. The [[Washington State Gambling Commission]] and local police raided Tony's Gaming and confiscated the inventory, stating that Curcio did not possess the proper permits.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nUnder increasing financial pressure, Curcio relapsed and began forging prescriptions on his computer. He later became aware that the police raid was due to influence from a real estate broker who had financial interest in a local casino. Curcio attempted to retain legal representation in the case but was denied services by local attorneys already debriefed by the real estate broker/casino owner.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nCurcio and several of his associates retaliated against the casino owner by breaking into his businesses and removing computers, files and documents from the offices he owned.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nCurcio continued to maintain an outward appearance that resembled a successful business owner and family man. He graduated from college, married his high school sweetheart, had two daughters and would later own a real estate investment company based in [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=GQ>{{cite web|last1=Kushner|first1=David|title=The All-American Bank Heist|url=http://74.220.215.94/~davidkus/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=109|publisher=GQ Magazine|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141130084955/http://74.220.215.94/~davidkus/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=109|archive-date=2014-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Curcio under surveillance.jpg|thumb|Anthony Curcio under the surveillance of the [[FBI]]]]\n\nHowever, he was living two different lives. As his addiction progressed, so did his involvement in illegal activities. By his mid 20s, Curcio had already organized several high-dollar thefts, scams, and loan-sharking schemes, and was also behind a sports memorabilia counterfeiting ring.<ref name=\"20/20\">{{cite web|last1=Benitez|first1=Gio|title=The (Almost) Perfect Crime|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ibKZq9cB2hU|publisher=ABC 20/20}}</ref>\nDespite having completed four drug and alcohol treatment programs, [[ABC News]] stated that Curcio was spending nearly $15,000 a month on his increasing drug habit which now also included [[cocaine]] and [[benzodiazepines]].<ref name=\"20/20\" />\n\nCurcio's real estate investment business took a heavy downturn when the economy collapsed in 2008, leaving him with several homes on the verge of foreclosure and vehicles near repossession among other outstanding personal debts.<ref name=GQ />\n\nWith assets and bank accounts depleting, Curcio hatched the idea to rob a Brink's armored car.\n\n== Brink's robbery ==\n\nFor three months, Curcio observed a [[Brink's]] [[Armored car (valuables)|armored car]] as it made deliveries to the [[Bank of America]] branch in [[Monroe, Washington]]. He took notes of the schedule, diagrammed locations of the bank's cameras, and noted the armored car's blind spots. He also estimated how much money was being transferred to the bank and how much was being removed via [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]].<ref name=\"20/20\"/>\n\nHe considered police protocol in responding to robberies and the location of the bank and decided on using a local creek to escape.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAfter weeks of hand-dredging the creek in [[Woods Creek, Washington|Woods Creek]] and a failed practice attempt at using a [[jet ski]] for the getaway, he changed his approach and created a cable pulley system to quickly pull himself, and large bags of cash, upstream using a connected canvas-wrapped [[Tubing (recreation)|inner tube]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ith |first1=Ian |title=6-year sentence in robbery with getaway inner tube |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2009548594_innertube28m.html |agency=The Seattle Times |date=July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219050947/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2009548594_innertube28m.html |archivedate=2014-12-19 }}</ref>\n\nCurcio's planning culminated with an advertisement he placed on [[Craigslist]] a few days before the robbery. The online ad sought 15 to 20 workers for a fictitious city cleanup project, promising $28.50 an hour.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The laborers were told to wear jeans, a blue shirt, work shoes, and a yellow safety vest. The ad also told the applicants they needed to bring safety goggles and a painter's mask. The ad directed them to meet in the Bank of America parking lot at the exact time Curcio planned to rob the armored car.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:18 Brinks truck.jpg|thumb|The [[Brink's]] armored car after the robbery  (September 30, 2008)]]\n\nOn September 30, 2008, Curcio, dressed identically to his decoy applicants, pretended to work the grounds near the bank. Wearing a blue shirt, jeans, yellow safety vest, work boots, and painter's mask, he [[Pepper spray|pepper-sprayed]] the Brink's armored car guard who was pushing a [[hand truck|dolly]] loaded with money into the bank.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The pepper spray forced the guard to reach for his eyes and release the cart that held the money.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} Curcio grabbed two bags of money, containing more than $400,000, and ran toward the creek. Meanwhile, police arrived to find the bank's parking lot filled with men matching the robber's description.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAt the water's edge, Curcio threw the money into the inner tube and pulled himself down the creek with the cables he had previously strung.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} He traveled about 200 yards upstream and exited the creek behind several businesses on the opposite side of the highway from the bank.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} Curcio removed his wig and worker's clothing that had been attached by [[Velcro]], revealing different attire underneath. He climbed into the trunk of a getaway vehicle driven by an associate and left.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sigerson|first1=Doc|title=AKA: DB Tuber|url=https://www.redfez.net/nonfiction/331/0|publisher=Red Fez}}</ref>\n\nCurcio's careful planning and unusual getaway gained national attention. The timing of the robbery came days after announcements of the [[Bailout of U.S. Financial System (2008)|government's bank bailout]] package that included Bank of America.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The unique robbery techniques gained notoriety for the mysterious robber who was referred to as the \"Craigslist Robber\" and \"D.B. Tuber\", after the 1970s hijacker [[D. B. Cooper]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} kaka\n\n== Arrest ==\n\nCurcio's undoing would come a month later when a homeless man reported to police that several weeks before the robbery he had seen a man drive up to the Bank of America parking lot and retrieve a disguise from behind a trash bin. The man found it suspicious enough to write down the license plate number of the car which he later provided to police. The car was registered to Curcio.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hefley|first1=Diana|title=Feds Charge Suspect in Armored Car Heist|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20081126/NEWS01/709259937|agency=The Everett Herald|date=November 26, 2008}}</ref> What the man had seen was one of Curcio's practice runs to ensure proper timing of the heist.\n\nAfter Curcio returned from a trip to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], the [[FBI]] began their surveillance of him as a suspect in the robbery. Local authorities retrieved his DNA from a drink bottle disposed of  by Curcio at a gas station and compared it to the DNA from the face mask and wig discarded a short distance from the scene of the robbery. The DNA samples matched and Curcio was arrested in [[Lake Stevens, Washington]] getting out of a luxury SUV with $17,000 in cash.<ref name=\"20/20\" />\n\nWith only [[circumstantial evidence]] connecting Curcio to the crime, he initially bonded out, but a month later (January 2009), his bond was revoked and he was returned to custody after being suspected of [[witness tampering]].<ref name=\"DOJ\"/>\n\nLater details would reveal that $220,000 was recovered after an associate of Curcio's came forward to make a deal with the FBI and local police. Curcio refused to cooperate with authorities and no other charges were ever filed against any of Curcio's unnamed co-conspirators.<ref name=CC /><ref name=\"HeistandHigh\"/>\n\nAll of the money except for what Curcio paid the getaway driver and other accomplices was eventually recovered.<ref name=CC />\n\n== Prison ==\n[[File:Curciojung-01.jpg|thumb|[[George Jung]] and Curcio in [[FCI La Tuna|La Tuna]], [[Federal Prison]]]]\n\nCurcio was sentenced to 72 months in federal prison and served his time in [[Federal Correctional Institution, Big Spring|FCI Big Spring]], [[FCI La Tuna]] and [[USP Coleman|Coleman Correctional Complex]].<ref name=curcio>{{cite web|last1=Curcio|first1=Anthony|title=acurcio.com|url=http://www.acurcio.com/|website=www.acurcio.com}}</ref>\n\nWhile being housed in FCI La Tuna, Curcio became close with fellow inmate [[George Jung]]. Jung encouraged Curcio to write a book, and put him in touch with author/biographer Dane Batty. The two soon began correspondence.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nDuring this time, Curcio was with two inmates who had previously assaulted another inmate. While prison authorities knew Curcio was not involved in the attack, authorities still held him \u2018under investigation\u2019 until the case had been resolved. Curcio spent seven months in [[solitary confinement]] for this affiliation. In solitary, he received beatings, witnessed suicides and would have cockroaches crawl all over his body at night. Upon his release, he wrote the book ''Heist and High'',<ref name=\"nishpublishing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|title=Heist And High - Nish Publishing|publisher=|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205051436/http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|archive-date=2014-12-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> promising to prevent others from making the same decisions he had made.<ref name=HeistandHigh /><ref name=IPM>{{cite web|last1=Manning|first1=Craig|title=Indie Ground Breaking Book: Heist and High|url=http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=1696|publisher=IPM}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the duration of his sentence, Curcio wrote and illustrated over 20 children's books, including one aimed at the children of incarcerated parents titled ''My Daddy\u2019s in Jail''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burykill|first1=Brett|title=The Ex-Con Who Wants to Explain Prison to Kids|url=\nhttps://www.vice.com/read/the-ex-con-who-wants-to-explain-prisons-to-kids|publisher=Vice Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://knkx.org/post/how-years-unforgivable-theft-and-lies-became-forgivable|title=How Years Of Unforgivable Theft And Lies Became Forgivable|last=Wing|first=Jennifer|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\nCurcio finished his incarceration at USP Coleman in Florida, where he completed a drug-treatment program and was released from custody April 2013.\n\n== Release ==\n\nCurcio was released April 4, 2013 and returned to the Seattle area, reuniting with his wife and two daughters. He has since been working with youth and giving presentations regarding drug abuse prevention and the importance of making positive choices. He speaks to middle schools, high schools and universities across the U.S.<ref name=curcio />\n\nCurcio has been featured on several media platforms using his story to increase awareness regarding addiction.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millman|first1=Michelle|title=How Painkillers Can Lead to Heroin Addiction|url=http://www.kirotv.com/videos/news/video-how-painkillers-can-lead-to-heroin-addiction/vC2w5Q/|publisher=KIRO 7 news}}</ref> His book, ''Heist and High''<ref name=\"nishpublishing.com\"/> (Nish Publishing, 286 pages), was released June 21, 2013 and has been the recipient of several awards.<ref name=IPM /><ref>{{cite web|title=2013 IndieFab Award Winners|url=https://indiefab.forewordreviews.com/books/heist-and-high/|publisher=FOREWORD}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.acurcio.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curcio, Anthony}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Monroe, Washington]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{POV|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Anthony Curcio\n|image=Anthony Curcio speaking to college football players.png\n|caption=Curcio speaking to college football players in August 2014\n|birth_place=[[Monroe, Washington]], U.S.\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1980|9|1}}\n|occupation= Speaker, author\n|spouse=\n|children=2\n|residence=\n}}\n'''Anthony J. Curcio''' (born September 1, 1980) is an American author, public speaker, and convicted robber.<ref name=CC>{{cite news|last1=Clarridge |first1=Christine |title=Inner-tube robber now free, warning about life of drugs, crime |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2024575267_dbtubertalksxml.html |agency=The Seattle Times |date=September 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219051132/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2024575267_dbtubertalksxml.html |archivedate=December 19, 2014 }}</ref>  In 2008, Curcio was responsible for one of the most elaborately planned armored car heists in U.S. history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doughery|first1=Phil|title=D.B. Tuber|url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=8829|website=HistoryLink.org|publisher=History Link}}</ref> He was eventually arrested and sentenced to six years in federal prison. Upon his release from prison he has devoted his life to working with youth in the field of drug abuse and crime prevention, speaking to students and athletes across the U.S.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esteban|first1=Michelle|title=D.B. Tuber dedicates life to warn others of dangers of drugs|url=http://www.komonews.com/news/local/DB-Tuber-out-of-prison-Warns-students-278808571.html|agency=KOMO 4 News|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> He has been featured in ''[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'',  ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV program)|20/20]]'', [[Fox News]], [[NPR]] and [[NBC]] among others.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nCurcio was born and raised in [[Monroe, Washington]]. As a teenager, he was popular and talented and voted captain of both football and basketball teams at [[Monroe High School (Washington)|Monroe High School]]<nowiki/>. Curcio broke many records in football and received several honors and awards for his play in both sports.<ref name=DOJ>{{cite web|title=Former High School Star Athlete Sentenced to Prison for Armored Car Robbery|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/waw/press/2009/jul/curcio.html|website=justice.gov|date=July 2009|publisher=The United States Attorney's Office|accessdate=<!--July 2009-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stangeland|first1=Brooke|title=Out of Prison, Real-Life Thomas Crown Looks Back on Almost-Perfect Heist|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/prison-real-life-thomas-crown-back-perfect-heist/story?id=19450132|agency=ABC news|date=June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCurcio would later go on to play football at his father's alma mater, the [[University of Idaho]], which had been his childhood dream.<ref>{{cite web|title=1999 Idaho Vandals - Sports Illustrated|url=http://157.166.253.202/football/college/rosters/1999/iia/|publisher=CNN/Sports Illustrated|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141130084954/http://157.166.253.202/football/college/rosters/1999/iia/|archive-date=2014-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> While returning a punt in practice, Curcio tore his [[anterior cruciate ligament]], ending his promising college football career and introducing him to the powerful pain killer [[Vicodin]]. Curcio quickly became addicted to the prescription pills.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stangeland|first1=Brooke|title=Reporter's Notebook: On the Trail of a Bank Robber|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/06/reporters-notebook-on-the-trail-of-a-bank-robber/|agency=ABC News|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref>\nSoon after, he began experiencing [[Drug withdrawal|withdrawals]] and even injured himself intentionally by kicking an oak coffee table repeatedly in order to obtain more pills. With family pressure, Curcio agreed to enter a drug/alcohol treatment facility.<ref name=HeistandHigh>{{cite book|last1=Batty|first1=Dane|last2=Curcio|first2=Anthony|title=Heist and High|url=http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|date=June 21, 2013|publisher=Nish Publishing Company|location=Portland, Oregon|isbn=098579450X|access-date=November 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205051436/http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing a 21-day in-patient program, Curcio, now sober, started his first business, called \"Tony\u2019s Gaming\", which bought and sold casino tables and other gaming merchandise. Curcio expanded his business by leasing a commercial space and adjacent storage. Within a few months of being open to the public, Tony's Gaming was unexpectedly shut down. The [[Washington State Gambling Commission]] and local police raided Tony's Gaming and confiscated the inventory, stating that Curcio did not possess the proper permits.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nUnder increasing financial pressure, Curcio relapsed and began forging prescriptions on his computer. He later became aware that the police raid was due to influence from a real estate broker who had financial interest in a local casino. Curcio attempted to retain legal representation in the case but was denied services by local attorneys already debriefed by the real estate broker/casino owner.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nCurcio and several of his associates retaliated against the casino owner by breaking into his businesses and removing computers, files and documents from the offices he owned.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nCurcio continued to maintain an outward appearance that resembled a successful business owner and family man. He graduated from college, married his high school sweetheart, had two daughters and would later own a real estate investment company based in [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=GQ>{{cite web|last1=Kushner|first1=David|title=The All-American Bank Heist|url=http://74.220.215.94/~davidkus/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=109|publisher=GQ Magazine|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141130084955/http://74.220.215.94/~davidkus/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=109|archive-date=2014-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Curcio under surveillance.jpg|thumb|Anthony Curcio under the surveillance of the [[FBI]]]]\n\nHowever, he was living two different lives. As his addiction progressed, so did his involvement in illegal activities. By his mid 20s, Curcio had already organized several high-dollar thefts, scams, and loan-sharking schemes, and was also behind a sports memorabilia counterfeiting ring.<ref name=\"20/20\">{{cite web|last1=Benitez|first1=Gio|title=The (Almost) Perfect Crime|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ibKZq9cB2hU|publisher=ABC 20/20}}</ref>\nDespite having completed four drug and alcohol treatment programs, [[ABC News]] stated that Curcio was spending nearly $15,000 a month on his increasing drug habit which now also included [[cocaine]] and [[benzodiazepines]].<ref name=\"20/20\" />\n\nCurcio's real estate investment business took a heavy downturn when the economy collapsed in 2008, leaving him with several homes on the verge of foreclosure and vehicles near repossession among other outstanding personal debts.<ref name=GQ />\n\nWith assets and bank accounts depleting, Curcio hatched the idea to rob a Brink's armored car.\n\n== Brink's robbery ==\n\nFor three months, Curcio observed a [[Brink's]] [[Armored car (valuables)|armored car]] as it made deliveries to the [[Bank of America]] branch in [[Monroe, Washington]]. He took notes of the schedule, diagrammed locations of the bank's cameras, and noted the armored car's blind spots. He also estimated how much money was being transferred to the bank and how much was being removed via [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]].<ref name=\"20/20\"/>\n\nHe considered police protocol in responding to robberies and the location of the bank and decided on using a local creek to escape.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAfter weeks of hand-dredging the creek in [[Woods Creek, Washington|Woods Creek]] and a failed practice attempt at using a [[jet ski]] for the getaway, he changed his approach and created a cable pulley system to quickly pull himself, and large bags of cash, upstream using a connected canvas-wrapped [[Tubing (recreation)|inner tube]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ith |first1=Ian |title=6-year sentence in robbery with getaway inner tube |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2009548594_innertube28m.html |agency=The Seattle Times |date=July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219050947/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2009548594_innertube28m.html |archivedate=2014-12-19 }}</ref>\n\nCurcio's planning culminated with an advertisement he placed on [[Craigslist]] a few days before the robbery. The online ad sought 15 to 20 workers for a fictitious city cleanup project, promising $28.50 an hour.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The laborers were told to wear jeans, a blue shirt, work shoes, and a yellow safety vest. The ad also told the applicants they needed to bring safety goggles and a painter's mask. The ad directed them to meet in the Bank of America parking lot at the exact time Curcio planned to rob the armored car.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:18 Brinks truck.jpg|thumb|The [[Brink's]] armored car after the robbery  (September 30, 2008)]]\n\nOn September 30, 2008, Curcio, dressed identically to his decoy applicants, pretended to work the grounds near the bank. Wearing a blue shirt, jeans, yellow safety vest, work boots, and painter's mask, he [[Pepper spray|pepper-sprayed]] the Brink's armored car guard who was pushing a [[hand truck|dolly]] loaded with money into the bank.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The pepper spray forced the guard to reach for his eyes and release the cart that held the money.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} Curcio grabbed two bags of money, containing more than $400,000, and ran toward the creek. Meanwhile, police arrived to find the bank's parking lot filled with men matching the robber's description.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAt the water's edge, Curcio threw the money into the inner tube and pulled himself down the creek with the cables he had previously strung.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} He traveled about 200 yards upstream and exited the creek behind several businesses on the opposite side of the highway from the bank.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} Curcio removed his wig and worker's clothing that had been attached by [[Velcro]], revealing different attire underneath. He climbed into the trunk of a getaway vehicle driven by an associate and left.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sigerson|first1=Doc|title=AKA: DB Tuber|url=https://www.redfez.net/nonfiction/331/0|publisher=Red Fez}}</ref>\n\nCurcio's careful planning and unusual getaway gained national attention. The timing of the robbery came days after announcements of the [[Bailout of U.S. Financial System (2008)|government's bank bailout]] package that included Bank of America.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} The unique robbery techniques gained notoriety for the mysterious robber who was referred to as the \"Craigslist Robber\" and \"D.B. Tuber\", after the 1970s hijacker [[D. B. Cooper]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n== Arrest ==\n\nCurcio's undoing would come a month later when a homeless man reported to police that several weeks before the robbery he had seen a man drive up to the Bank of America parking lot and retrieve a disguise from behind a trash bin. The man found it suspicious enough to write down the license plate number of the car which he later provided to police. The car was registered to Curcio.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hefley|first1=Diana|title=Feds Charge Suspect in Armored Car Heist|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20081126/NEWS01/709259937|agency=The Everett Herald|date=November 26, 2008}}</ref> What the man had seen was one of Curcio's practice runs to ensure proper timing of the heist.\n\nAfter Curcio returned from a trip to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], the [[FBI]] began their surveillance of him as a suspect in the robbery. Local authorities retrieved his DNA from a drink bottle disposed of  by Curcio at a gas station and compared it to the DNA from the face mask and wig discarded a short distance from the scene of the robbery. The DNA samples matched and Curcio was arrested in [[Lake Stevens, Washington]] getting out of a luxury SUV with $17,000 in cash.<ref name=\"20/20\" />\n\nWith only [[circumstantial evidence]] connecting Curcio to the crime, he initially bonded out, but a month later (January 2009), his bond was revoked and he was returned to custody after being suspected of [[witness tampering]].<ref name=\"DOJ\"/>\n\nLater details would reveal that $220,000 was recovered after an associate of Curcio's came forward to make a deal with the FBI and local police. Curcio refused to cooperate with authorities and no other charges were ever filed against any of Curcio's unnamed co-conspirators.<ref name=CC /><ref name=\"HeistandHigh\"/>\n\nAll of the money except for what Curcio paid the getaway driver and other accomplices was eventually recovered.<ref name=CC />\n\n== Prison ==\n[[File:Curciojung-01.jpg|thumb|[[George Jung]] and Curcio in [[FCI La Tuna|La Tuna]], [[Federal Prison]]]]\n\nCurcio was sentenced to 72 months in federal prison and served his time in [[Federal Correctional Institution, Big Spring|FCI Big Spring]], [[FCI La Tuna]] and [[USP Coleman|Coleman Correctional Complex]].<ref name=curcio>{{cite web|last1=Curcio|first1=Anthony|title=acurcio.com|url=http://www.acurcio.com/|website=www.acurcio.com}}</ref>\n\nWhile being housed in FCI La Tuna, Curcio became close with fellow inmate [[George Jung]]. Jung encouraged Curcio to write a book, and put him in touch with author/biographer Dane Batty. The two soon began correspondence.<ref name=HeistandHigh />\n\nDuring this time, Curcio was with two inmates who had previously assaulted another inmate. While prison authorities knew Curcio was not involved in the attack, authorities still held him \u2018under investigation\u2019 until the case had been resolved. Curcio spent seven months in [[solitary confinement]] for this affiliation. In solitary, he received beatings, witnessed suicides and would have cockroaches crawl all over his body at night. Upon his release, he wrote the book ''Heist and High'',<ref name=\"nishpublishing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|title=Heist And High - Nish Publishing|publisher=|access-date=2014-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205051436/http://www.nishpublishing.com/heist-and-high/|archive-date=2014-12-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> promising to prevent others from making the same decisions he had made.<ref name=HeistandHigh /><ref name=IPM>{{cite web|last1=Manning|first1=Craig|title=Indie Ground Breaking Book: Heist and High|url=http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=1696|publisher=IPM}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the duration of his sentence, Curcio wrote and illustrated over 20 children's books, including one aimed at the children of incarcerated parents titled ''My Daddy\u2019s in Jail''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burykill|first1=Brett|title=The Ex-Con Who Wants to Explain Prison to Kids|url=\nhttps://www.vice.com/read/the-ex-con-who-wants-to-explain-prisons-to-kids|publisher=Vice Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://knkx.org/post/how-years-unforgivable-theft-and-lies-became-forgivable|title=How Years Of Unforgivable Theft And Lies Became Forgivable|last=Wing|first=Jennifer|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\nCurcio finished his incarceration at USP Coleman in Florida, where he completed a drug-treatment program and was released from custody April 2013.\n\n== Release ==\n\nCurcio was released April 4, 2013 and returned to the Seattle area, reuniting with his wife and two daughters. He has since been working with youth and giving presentations regarding drug abuse prevention and the importance of making positive choices. He speaks to middle schools, high schools and universities across the U.S.<ref name=curcio />\n\nCurcio has been featured on several media platforms using his story to increase awareness regarding addiction.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millman|first1=Michelle|title=How Painkillers Can Lead to Heroin Addiction|url=http://www.kirotv.com/videos/news/video-how-painkillers-can-lead-to-heroin-addiction/vC2w5Q/|publisher=KIRO 7 news}}</ref> His book, ''Heist and High''<ref name=\"nishpublishing.com\"/> (Nish Publishing, 286 pages), was released June 21, 2013 and has been the recipient of several awards.<ref name=IPM /><ref>{{cite web|title=2013 IndieFab Award Winners|url=https://indiefab.forewordreviews.com/books/heist-and-high/|publisher=FOREWORD}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.acurcio.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curcio, Anthony}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Monroe, Washington]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n", "name_user": "2001:1c01:3cc1:5a00:54ed:821d:d1cb:b524", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBrink's robbery)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Curcio"}
